Certainly! Below is a Perl script that reads a log file line by line, filters out lines containing specific keywords passed as command line arguments, and writes the filtered lines to a new output file.

```perl
#!/usr/bin/perl
use strict;
use warnings;

# Check if the number of arguments is sufficient
if (@ARGV < 3) {
    die "Usage: $0 <logfile> <outputfile> <keyword1> [<keyword2> ... <keywordN>]\n";
}

# Extract the input and output file names from the arguments
my $logfile = shift @ARGV;
my $outputfile = shift @ARGV;

# The remaining arguments are the keywords
my @keywords = @ARGV;

# Open the log file for reading
open my $log_fh, '<', $logfile or die "Could not open '$logfile' for reading: $!\n";

# Open the output file for writing
open my $out_fh, '>', $outputfile or die "Could not open '$outputfile' for writing: $!\n";

# Read the log file line by line
while (my $line = <$log_fh>) {
    # Check if the line contains any of the keywords
    my $contains_keyword = 0;
    foreach my $keyword (@keywords) {
        if (index($line, $keyword) != -1) {
            $contains_keyword = 1;
            last;
        }
    }

    # If the line does not contain any of the keywords, write it to the output file
    if (!$contains_keyword) {
        print $out_fh $line;
    }
}

# Close the file handles
close $log_fh;
close $out_fh;

print "Filtered lines have been written to '$outputfile'.\n";
```

### Usage
To use this script, save it to a file, for example, `filter_log.pl`, and make it executable:

```sh
chmod +x filter_log.pl
```

Then run the script with the log file, output file, and keywords as arguments:

```sh
./filter_log.pl input.log output.log keyword1 keyword2 keyword3
```

This will read `input.log`, filter out lines containing `keyword1`, `keyword2`, or `keyword3`, and write the remaining lines to `output.log`.

